objectArray.title: Takeo City: Takeo Okusu
objectArray.text:
Takeo Okusu, the sacred tree of Takeo Shrine, is the seventh largest tree in Japan. It is said to be over 3,000 years old.
Simply taking in its imposing presence as its roots spread across the ground is both breathtaking and empowering.

objectArray.title: Takeo City: Takeo Shrine
objectArray.text:
Takeo Shrine at the eastern foot of Mifuneyama is a historic shrine with ancient documents (nationally designated Important Cultural Property) dating from the mid-Heian period to the late Muromachi period. Its chief deity is Takenouchi no Sukune.
Its torii gate is called Hizen Torii and has a unique banana shape.

objectArray.title: Imari City: Imariwan Bridge
objectArray.text:
Imariwan Bridge is located at Imari Port in Imari City, Saga Prefecture. It connects the towns of Kusuku Yamashiro and Seto.
It features round pipes in the upper part of the bridge.

objectArray.title: Tara Town: Floating Torii Gate
objectArray.text:
Tara, known as "the town where the moon's gravitational pull is visible," boasts Japan's largest tidal difference of up to 6 meters.
The floating torii gates change their appearance with the ebb and flow of the tides. The crimson gates floating in the vast Ariake Sea are truly a spectacular sight.

objectArray.title: Karatsu City: Nanatsugama Caves
objectArray.text:
The Nanatsugama Caves, a designated natural monument of Japan, are spectacular caves formed by the raging waves of the Genkai Sea.
The name is indicative of its 7 caves, and the scenery strikes onlookers by the wonders of nature.

objectArray.title: Karatsu City: Kyaranko Beach
objectArray.text:
Kyaranko Beach is an artificial swimming area in Yobuko, Karatsu next to Kodomo Fishing Port.
You can watch sea life along the man-made beach and have access to a playground, so it's a great place to bring the family.

objectArray.title: Karatsu City: Hikiyama Exhibition Hall
objectArray.text:
Fourteen hikiyama floats come out in full force during Karatsu Kunchi, a fall festival for a bountiful harvest (held annually from November 2 to 4).
The floats are a rare glimpse of superb craftsmanship in a multitude of beautiful forms. They have been recognized as Important Tangible Folk Cultural Property of Saga Prefecture.

objectArray.title: Karatsu City: Suginohara Farm
objectArray.text:
On the edge of Kabeshima Island is a pasture surrounded by the sea. Cows spend their days grazing on the grassy plains.
A promenade has been built to provide access to the seaside. The sea breeze is truly wonderful in the summer.

objectArray.title: Imari City: Okawachiyama
objectArray.text:
Okawachiyama, the Village of Secret Kilns, gave life to a culture of exceptional pottery. The Saga Domain's Nabeshima Clan's kiln is the origin of Nabeshima porcelain, prized work of exceeding quality.
Its over 300 years of history and tradition can be felt today in the rows of brick chimneys and potteries.

objectArray.title: Takeo City: Mifuneyama
objectArray.text:
Mifuneyama is also known as Karafuneyama as the mountain resembles a karafune, or Chinese boat. At its western foot lies Mifuneyama Rakuen.
About 200,000 azaleas decorate the landscape. In spring, 2,000 cherry trees and a 170-year-old wisteria bloom in full. In fall, you can witness the beauty of the changing leaves.

objectArray.title: Ureshino City: Tea Plantation
objectArray.text: Ureshino tea is known for its glossy, round, deep green leaves and the potency of its aroma and flavor. It is famous for the way the taste and aroma transform each time it is poured due to the way the flavor is extracted as the tea slowly opens inside the teapot.

objectArray.title: Ariake Sea Mudflat
objectArray.text:
The Ariake Sea Mudflat is the largest tidal flat in Japan, making up roughly 40% of the country's tidal flats.
With a tidal difference of 6 meters, it is home to a variety of wildlife that make for a rare sight, such as mudskippers and eel gobies.

objectArray.title: Saga City: Saga Castle History Museum
objectArray.text:
A historical museum at the Saga Castle Ruins, where part of the main keep has been faithfully reconstructed true to the Bakumatsu period.
The museum introduces the fascinating "Bakumatsu Restoration Saga," which spurred Japan's modernization. It is credited as the largest wooden building reconstruction in Japan.

objectArray.title: Yoshinogari Town: Yoshinogari Historical Park
objectArray.text:
One of the largest moat settlement ruins from the Yayoi period in Japan. The watchtower and pit dwellings have been restored to their original likeness, and visitors can experience the atmosphere of the past.
The excavation of the "mysterious area" at Hiyoshi Shrine was completed in 2023.

objectArray.title: Arita Town: Porcelain Park
objectArray.text:
Arita Porcelain Park is a theme park that can only be found in the area that has influenced pottery around the globe since the 17th century.
The faithful replica of the Zwinger Palace, a magnificent building of early 18th century Baroque Germany, is a spectacle not to be missed.

objectArray.title: Ureshino City: Ureshino Onsen
objectArray.text:
One of the top three hot springs in Japan for skin care. One dip in the silky water and you'll never want to leave.
Experience the local history and customs at the densely clustered traditional inns.

objectArray.title: Shiroishi Town: Nuinoike
objectArray.text:
The Nuinoike Pond is a power spot of water. It was completely dried up for 40 years, but in 2001, it sprang back to life.
The water that now gushes forth with abandon has been named "kinmyousui," and many come to draw from it.

objectArray.title: Saga City: Saga Station
objectArray.text:
The representative station of Saga City, prefectural capital of Saga Prefecture. All kinds of trains stop here, including limited express ones.
In recent years, it has been involved with the 2024 Japan Games & National Sports Festival for People with a Disability. Both its north and south exits are undergoing renovation.

objectArray.title: Saga City: Shichimensou
objectArray.text:
A fall staple of the Ariake Sea is the "autumn leaves of the sea," so called because of the coloration that rivals that of an autumnal mountainside.
The change can be seen every year between late October and mid-November.

objectArray.title: Ogi City: Kiyomizu Waterfall
objectArray.text:
The waterfall is located upstream of the Kiyomizu River, one of the 100 Remarkable Waters of Japan. It is 75m high and 13m wide with a clear stream flowing vertically down.
By the waterfall are a number of carp restaurants serving fish from the famous water. In the summer, it becomes lively with visitors escaping the heat.

objectArray.title: Saga City: Furuyu Kumanokawa Onsen
objectArray.text:
The waters of Furuyu Kumanokawa Onsen are a mild 38 degrees and leave a nice, slippery feeling on the skin; features earning it the name nuruyu or lukewarm waters.
And because the water isn't too hot, one can soak for a long while until warmed to the core.

objectArray.title: Saga City: Balloon Fiesta
objectArray.text:
As November begins, balloonists from across Japan and the world gather in Saga City for the Saga International Balloon Fiesta, the biggest hot air balloon competition in Asia.
The competition period for 2023 is Wednesday, November 1st through Sunday, November 5th. Please check the official website for details of each year's schedule.
